Okay, that's it.

00:26.789 --> 00:29.580
You guys are always talking about
the llama incident.

00:29.664 --> 00:31.539
What is the llama incident?

00:31.622 --> 00:34.414
I don't think we're always
talking about it.

00:34.497 --> 00:37.206
Yeah, what conversations
would that even fit into?

00:37.289 --> 00:38.747
A lot.

00:38.831 --> 00:40.664
I would've had extras but you know,
the llama incident.

00:40.747 --> 00:42.747
Last time he came,
there was a llama stampede.

00:42.831 --> 00:46.831
My t-shirt launcher is still filled with
knockout gas from the llama incident.

00:46.914 --> 00:49.706
I've seen you walk a tightrope
over stampeding llamas.

00:49.789 --> 00:51.081
Llama incident.

00:51.164 --> 00:52.081
Llama incident.

00:52.206 --> 00:54.622
[both alternating]
Lla. Ma. In. Ci. Dent.

00:54.706 --> 00:57.622
[both] Llama incident.

00:57.706 --> 00:59.664
Well, we might be able to
llama our way out of this.

00:59.747 --> 01:01.789
Oh, just like
the llama incident.

01:01.872 --> 01:04.039
Oh, I hadn't realized
we talk about it so much.

01:04.123 --> 01:06.706
Looks like we're gonna have to let him
into the llama club, Milo.

01:06.789 --> 01:12.622
All right, then. Sit back, relax and get
ready to hear the llama story.

01:12.706 --> 01:15.289
Actually, don't sit back
because you'll fall to your doom.

01:15.372 --> 01:16.706
It was last fall.

01:16.789 --> 01:19.289
Melissa was stuck on a tightrope
over the football field.

01:19.372 --> 01:22.414
Milo, I can't do this much longer.
What's the plan?

01:22.497 --> 01:25.123
Not sure yet but
I'm working on it.

01:25.206 --> 01:28.039
Why are there all these llamas
at the football game?

01:28.123 --> 01:29.123
[groans]

01:29.206 --> 01:30.372
[Milo] And that was
the llama incident.

01:30.455 --> 01:33.455
Hold on. How did the llamas
wind up at the football game?

01:33.580 --> 01:35.039
Okay, let me back up.

01:35.123 --> 01:36.622
Back at the
turn of the century...

01:36.706 --> 01:39.164
-[Zack] Really? It starts in 1900?
-[Milo] No, this century.

01:39.248 --> 01:40.372
[Milo] The year 2000.

01:40.455 --> 01:41.998
[Zack] Oh, okay. Go on.

01:42.081 --> 01:45.164
[Milo] A man named Edwin Garner came into
a large inheritance.

01:45.248 --> 01:47.414
[Melissa] But the inheritance
wasn't money.

01:47.497 --> 01:50.081
What are these
llamas doing here?

01:50.164 --> 01:52.664
[in Boston accent] I told you, Uncle Irwin
left me the llama farm.

01:52.747 --> 01:53.831
Just not the farm part.

01:53.914 --> 01:55.539
[Zack] Stop. Stop there.

01:55.622 --> 01:57.747
Why does he have such a thick
Boston accent?

01:57.831 --> 02:00.330
-Oh, he was originally from Boston.
-Oh, okay.

02:00.414 --> 02:02.789
But I think you backtracked too far.
Jump ahead.

02:02.872 --> 02:05.539
Oh, okay. So, Garner bought
a little theater in town,

02:05.622 --> 02:07.330
a little 99-seat place,
Equity Waiver.

02:07.414 --> 02:09.747
Anyway, 15 years later
he had a whole string of them,

02:09.831 --> 02:13.497
and there was an avant garde play festival
using Garner's llamas in the cast.

02:13.580 --> 02:15.747
[Melissa] There were shows
like Hello Dolly Llama,

02:15.831 --> 02:19.206
Annie Get Your Llama,
Death of A Sales Llama.

02:19.289 --> 02:21.539
Some of the titles
were better than others.

02:21.622 --> 02:24.414
[Milo] " Llamalet, it's Hamlet
but with Llamas."

02:24.497 --> 02:26.123
Well, I guess that
quote says it all.

02:26.206 --> 02:28.414
I always confuse
camels and llamas.

02:28.497 --> 02:30.706
Are llamas furry?
Or is their skin like a briefcase?

02:30.789 --> 02:32.706
Furry. Neither is like a briefcase.

02:32.789 --> 02:34.164
I wonder what
I'm thinking of.

02:34.248 --> 02:36.497
-A briefcase?
-That's it.

02:36.580 --> 02:38.580
[Melissa] So, we're at
Garner's theater,

02:38.664 --> 02:40.706
and all things considered,
the play was going pretty well.

02:40.789 --> 02:42.539
Hamlet had just
asked for forgiveness

02:42.622 --> 02:45.164
but Laertes wasn't
having any part of it.

02:45.289 --> 02:46.872
I think.

02:46.956 --> 02:50.081
And I thought it was hard to understand
Shakespeare in human.

02:50.164 --> 02:52.831
[Melissa] That's right around
where Murphy's Law kicked in.

02:54.914 --> 02:56.123
[llamas gasp]

03:00.872 --> 03:01.872
[Milo] My backpack.

03:02.747 --> 03:04.831
Stop that llama!

