-[polar bear roaring]
-[Melissa shrieking]

04:27.998 --> 04:29.872
[Milo] And I got
my backpack back.

04:29.956 --> 04:32.872
Hold on, hold on, hold on.
What's with the polar bear?

04:32.956 --> 04:35.330
And how did you get from the glacier
to the football game?

04:35.414 --> 04:38.664
Well, we couldn't just
leave those llamas on the iceberg.

04:38.747 --> 04:42.289
So, I used my t-shirt cannon to shoot
knockout gas at the polar bear,

04:42.372 --> 04:44.831
which we used to frighten the llamas
in a southerly direction.

04:44.914 --> 04:47.539
From there, it was a simple matter
of a dog sled,

04:47.622 --> 04:49.956
seaplane and public bus system
back to town.

04:52.956 --> 04:54.539
Okay, mission accomplished.

04:54.622 --> 04:56.580
We just have to get
these quadruped thespians

04:56.664 --> 04:58.497
back to their respective theaters.

04:58.580 --> 05:00.706
But they seemed confused
and unmotivated.

05:00.789 --> 05:01.998
How do you
motivate a llama?

05:02.081 --> 05:03.956
Well, we could lure them with pistachios.

05:04.039 --> 05:04.872
Pistachios?

05:04.956 --> 05:06.831
Didn't you know that
llamas love pistachios?

05:06.914 --> 05:07.831
You're asking me?

05:07.914 --> 05:09.872
I thought they had
skin like a briefcase.

05:09.956 --> 05:12.455
[Dakota] Who knew pistachio
gelatin was so heavy?

05:12.539 --> 05:14.872
Who knew pistachio gelatin existed?

05:14.956 --> 05:17.539
I could've sworn I had some pistachios
in here, somewhere.

05:20.664 --> 05:22.039
[bird chirping]

05:24.789 --> 05:27.497
Hey, I found them.
Oh, that works, too.

05:27.580 --> 05:30.372
Milo, what do I do?

05:30.455 --> 05:33.372
[all grunting curiously]

05:33.455 --> 05:35.872
If I were you,
I'd probably run.

05:37.123 --> 05:39.872
-So, then you went to the football game?
-Let's see.

05:39.956 --> 05:42.664
Hamlet, ballet, graduation,
beauty salon, cargo ship,

05:42.747 --> 05:44.081
glacier, bus,
pistachio gelatin,

05:44.164 --> 05:46.039
-giant spool of wire...
-[Zack] Giant spool of wire?

05:46.123 --> 05:48.580
Oh, right.
Got ahead of myself.

05:48.664 --> 05:51.789
So, Melissa ran as fast as she could, but
the llamas were closing in.

05:51.872 --> 05:53.747
She ran right into
the football stadium.

05:53.831 --> 05:54.872
Hey!

05:54.956 --> 05:56.956
[Milo] With the llamas
hot on her heels.

05:57.039 --> 05:58.372
She's with me!

05:58.455 --> 05:59.914
So, who are the llamas with?

06:00.372 --> 06:01.831
Hut! Hey!

06:05.831 --> 06:06.914
Take this!

06:10.580 --> 06:11.580
[Melissa yells]

06:14.831 --> 06:17.914
Your hooves are hard and leathery
like a briefcase.

06:17.998 --> 06:20.622
♪ One thing I can promise
I've been all across this nation ♪

06:20.706 --> 06:23.998
♪ Never seen so many llamas
So here's my punctuation ♪

06:24.081 --> 06:25.289
♪ Llama, comma
Llama, comma ♪

06:25.372 --> 06:27.956
♪ Llama, comma
Llama, comma llama, comma ♪

06:28.039 --> 06:29.998
♪ Llama, Oxford comma and llama ♪

06:30.081 --> 06:31.123
Yeah!

06:31.206 --> 06:33.872
-[whooping]
-♪ Llama,llama, llama ♪

06:37.414 --> 06:39.956
That's right, bring it up here.
Now, tie it to the railing.

06:40.039 --> 06:42.414
There you go,
one drum of cable.

06:42.497 --> 06:44.622
No, I said one
drum for Mabel.

06:44.706 --> 06:46.039
She left hers at home.

06:46.123 --> 06:49.580
Oh, I get it.
Drum of cable, drum for Mabel.

06:49.664 --> 06:53.622
Boy, is my face red. I mean, they sound a
lot alike and then they rhyme and all,

06:53.706 --> 06:57.455
but why would I think
you need a big drum of cable up here?

06:57.539 --> 07:01.039
And it was a lot of effort
getting it up these stairs.

07:01.123 --> 07:03.414
[Milo] This went on
for several hours.

07:03.497 --> 07:06.747
-[rapid tapping]
-And... Wait, what's that noise?

07:06.872 --> 07:08.081
Shoo!
Stop that.

07:08.164 --> 07:09.497
Go away, woodpecker.

07:09.580 --> 07:11.372
Maybe we can
distract him.

07:11.455 --> 07:12.789
What do woodpeckers like to eat?

07:12.872 --> 07:15.580
-Uh, branches.
-Pistachio trees.

07:15.664 --> 07:18.123
Yes, but the pistacia vera
is a very sturdy wood.

07:18.206 --> 07:21.081
That should give me enough time to tell
you about the seat belts.

07:21.164 --> 07:22.998
[tapping continues]

07:23.081 --> 07:24.248
-Keep going.
-Anyway,

07:24.330 --> 07:26.831
Melissa was getting pretty tired of
running from llamas.

07:26.914 --> 07:29.998
Milo, a little help here.
I'm about to be llama chow.

07:30.081 --> 07:32.081
I've got it, seat belts.

07:32.164 --> 07:34.789
Whatever you're doing,
do it better.

07:37.789 --> 07:39.956
Melissa, grab the seat belt.

07:45.123 --> 07:47.414
Milo, this isn't working.

07:50.039 --> 07:52.206
[exclaims]

07:52.872 --> 07:57.706
Whoa!

07:57.789 --> 07:59.914
Oops, sorry.
I didn't mean to throw it that high.

07:59.998 --> 08:01.914
I was just startled
by all these llamas.

08:01.998 --> 08:05.123
Milo, I can't do this much longer.
What's the plan?

08:05.206 --> 08:07.831
Not sure yet but
I'm working on it.

08:07.914 --> 08:11.580
Why are there all these llamas
at the football game?

08:11.664 --> 08:15.164
[Milo] And that's basically it.
The llama story. The end.

08:15.248 --> 08:17.706
The end? What do you mean?

08:17.789 --> 08:19.539
She's about to fall
into stampeding llamas.

08:19.622 --> 08:21.081
That's how we started.

08:21.164 --> 08:23.414
Oh, well, you know she got down because
she's right here.

08:23.497 --> 08:26.706
